Such motif is commonly found on other stone memorial pillars.

objectimagedescription:
The sanctum contains the top parts (stūpi) of the two śikharas.

These artefacts are often re-used as śivaliṅgas which does not appear to be the case here (no signs of religious activities could be seen).

objectimagedescription:
The central part of the lintel is adorned with a carving representing a central flower with petal-like motifs spreading from it.

A similar motif is carved on the southern temple. This combination of motifs is not seen elsewhere in the Karnali Basin.

objectimagedescription:
View of the central register of the frieze, with a sitted goddess. A devotee is worshipping the deity on each side. The attributes held by the goddess are difficult to identify.

The image is locally identified as a representation of Kālikā.
objectimagecaption: Ugratārā Mandira, detail of Durgā Devī frieze,view from east; photo by David C. Andolfatto; 2015-04-07

objectimagedescription:
The frieze is divided in five registers. To the left is a lion (or a buffalo?), next to it are two sitted devotees, turned towards the central register, constituted by a sitted female deity surrounded by two devotees. The same order is then repeated on the right side (two devotees, a lion).

The object must originally be a temple's lintel.
objectimagecaption: Ugratārā Mandira, Durgā Devī frieze,view from east; photo by David C. Andolfatto; 2015-04-07

objectimagedescription:
According to the local tradition the two pillars were used (seemingly up until the early 20th century) during human sacrifices (narabali). The person to be sacrificed would place its hands on the tenons of the pillars, while the priest would come behind and cut the throat.

The pillars were orginally part of a monument such as a pavilion or a śikhara temple.
objectimagecaption: Ugratārā Mandira, pair of stone pillars, view from south; photo by David C. Andolfatto; 2015-04-07

objectimagedescription:
The deity is represented holding severed heads, a large dagger (?) and a snake (?). She also seems to be holding a snake in her first right arm, and to be standing on a stylised dragon. These attributes would tend to identify a representation of Kālī.

The dimensions are: 29 x 25 5 cm
objectimagecaption: Ugratārā Mandira, Bhairava Mandira, statue of an eight-armed goddess, view from east; photo by David C. Andolfatto; 2015-04-07
Ugratārā Mandira, shrine of Kālī, statue of Kālī, view from east; photo by David C. Andolfatto; 2015-04-07

Each of the three artefacts must have originally be placed in separate temples.

objectimagedescription: View of the top of the artefact, showing a rectangular and a circular cavity. The rectangular cavity may indicate the use of metal staples to strengthen the connection between the base of the pillar and the shaft. The circular cavity, evoking a mortar for pounding grains, must be a mortise. Traces of abrasion indicate that the object could have been used as a mortar.

objectimagedescription: The door is constituted by exceptionally high doorjambs. The lintel and doorjambs are decorated with motifs of spirals, a common motif on the door of 13th-16th century śikhara temples of the Karnali basin.
objectimagecaption: Śambhunātha Mandira, door to the sanctum, view from NW; photo by David C. Andolfatto; 2018-05-06

objectimagedescription: Architectural elements from medieval monuments are insterted in the masonry.
objectimagecaption: Śambhunātha Mandira, door to the sanctum, view from N; photo by David C. Andolfatto; 2018-05-06

objectimagedescription:
Two large carved friezes from medieval monuments are insterted in the massonry. 

The finial above the sanctum is a gilt metal gajūra coming a workshop in the Kathmandu valley.

The roof is covered by stone slabs.
objectimagecaption: Śambhunātha Mandira, back wall, view from S; photo by David C. Andolfatto; 2018-05-06
Śambhunātha Mandira, minature śikhara 003, view from W; photo by David C. Andolfatto; 2018-05-06

objectimagedescription: Three similar elements showing two affronted lions (?) are inserted in the masonry of the temple's eastern outer wall. They are commonly placed in the pediments of śikhara temples.
objectimagecaption: Śambhunātha Mandira, architectural detail, view from E; photo by David C. Andolfatto; 2018-05-06
